    return df.sort_values(by=column,ascending=False)[:n]

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA

# Excel
df = pd.read_excel(r'C:\Users\\Desktop\14-191.xlsx')
df[''] = pd.to_datetime(df[''])
ts_data = df[['', 'PM2.5']]
ts_data.set_index('', inplace=True)

# 
ts_data_daily = ts_data.resample('D').mean()

# PM2.5
plt.plot(ts_data)
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('')
plt.title('')
plt.show()

# ARIMA
model = ARIMA(ts_data_daily, order=(1, 1, 1))
results = model.fit()
forecast = results.forecast(steps=365)  # 365

# 
print(forecast)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX

# Excel
df = pd.read_excel(r'C:\Users\\Desktop\14-191.xlsx')
df[''] = pd.to_datetime(df[''])
ts_data = df[['', 'PM2.5']]
ts_data.set_index('', inplace=True)

# 
ts_data_daily = ts_data.resample('D').mean()

# PM2.5
plt.plot(ts_data_daily)
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('')
plt.title('')
plt.show()

# SARIMA
model = SARIMAX(ts_data_daily, order=(1, 1, 1), seasonal_order=(1, 0, 1, 7))
results = model.fit()
forecast = results.forecast(steps=365)  # 365
